	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Measures announced to ease pressures on Ghanaian poultry farmers</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>﻿</p><p>In May 2011, in the face of high global cereals prices, Ghanaian poultry farmers called on their government to establish a buffer stock of yellow corn ‘to help stabilise prices’. Poultry farmers’ leaders argued that ‘the creation of a buffer stock for yellow corn would provide an opportunity for all-year-round supply to farmers to perform their work smoothly.’ The high price of vaccines and day-old chicks were seen as compounding the problem of high feed costs faced by the sector. These problems came on top of ‘stiff competition from imported chicken which was comparatively cheaper on the market’.</p><p>Poultry producers and the government of Ghana have been holding a series of meetings to work on issues for the industry, and following a further meeting, the country’s vice president called on the Ministry of Food and Agriculture to release yellow corn from buffer stocks for use by poultry farmers to ‘avoid the perennial importation of poultry feed which had over the years aggravated [the financial situation of Ghanaian poultry farmers]’. In parallel with this, the Agricultural Development Bank announced ‘a budget of $15 million to import 32,000 tonnes of soybeans for poultry farmers’. This came on top of loans already made to promote cultivation of ‘yellow corn and soybeans for the poultry industry’.</p><p>Mr Kwadwo Asante, Chairman of the Ghana National Association of Poultry Farmers, called for closer cooperation with the Ministry of Food and Agriculture to ensure a smoother functioning of the policy dialogue process in future. He said that without the remedial measures now agreed, ‘the collapse of most poultry farms’ would have been imminent, given the rising input costs.</p>
		
		
