<i>Modernghana.com</i>, ‘Poultry farmers appeal for support’, 1 June 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.modernghana.com/news/331891/22/poultry-farmers-appeal-for-support.html" target="_self">http://www.modernghana.com/news/331891/22/poultry-farmers-appeal-for-sup...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Elsewhere in West Africa, governments have resorted to the use of trade-policy measures to ease the financial pressures on the poultry sector. In Ghana, however, the government has opted for various input-support measures designed to ease the financial pressures on the sector. This raises important issues about the nature of the future regional policy framework that will be pursued to promote poultry- sector development within the region.</p><p>If some governments use trade-policy measures which limit imports, while other government use input-subsidy measures but allow unrestricted imports, any liberalisation of intra-regional trade in poultry-meat is likely to lead to trade diversion, or if governments seek to maintain the integrity of their national trade-policy measures, increased smuggling.</p><p>This poses serious problems for regional poultry-sector policy formulation. One avenue would be for the kind of sector dialogue process that has taken place nationally within Ghana between poultry producers and government to be promoted at the regional level. The aim of such a regional poultry-sector dialogue process could be to promote a common approach to poultry-sector development, including the use of input-support measures and trade-policy measures.</p>
		</div>
		
